<subSubSection box="[151,429,1050,1077]" pageId="3" pageNumber="344" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,429,1050,1077]" box="[151,429,1050,1077]" pageId="3" pageNumber="344">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,429,1050,1077]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="3" pageNumber="344" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,429,1050,1077]" pageId="3" pageNumber="344">
The 
<taxonomicName authority="(Meyrick)" baseAuthorityName="Meyrick" box="[207,347,1050,1077]" class="Insecta" family="Opostegidae" genus="Pseudopostega" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="344" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="machaerias">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[207,347,1050,1077]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="344">machaerias</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="344" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1123,1617]" pageId="3" pageNumber="344">
Externally, species are characterized by dark markings (a spot or fascia) on the dorsal margin of the forewing; pure white, indistinctive frontal tuft of piliform scales on the vertex of the head. In the male genitalia, the uncus is comprised of two wide, short or long lateral lobes; the gnathos is a large plate with a distinctive, wide, non-spiny caudal process; and the vinculum has a distinctive, long, apically slightly widened, rod-like juxta (
<figureCitation box="[1192,1259,1231,1257]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1904,1928]" captionTargetBox="[177,1411,192,1870]" captionTargetId="figure-18@4.[169,1417,181,1880]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 1. Pictorial diagnostic tool for identification of Oriental Pseudopostega species groups (Note: the morphological structures are drawn in different scales). * – except for P. similantis with an indistinctive dorsal spot; ** – formerly the nigrimaculella group; *** – Mediterranean P. matrona sp. nov., described below" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4554948" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4554948/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="344">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). In the female genitalia, apophyses are long; anal papillae with two rounded, closely set lobes or modified into a single, oval element (
<figureCitation box="[223,289,1303,1329]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1904,1928]" captionTargetBox="[177,1411,192,1870]" captionTargetId="figure-18@4.[169,1417,181,1880]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 1. Pictorial diagnostic tool for identification of Oriental Pseudopostega species groups (Note: the morphological structures are drawn in different scales). * – except for P. similantis with an indistinctive dorsal spot; ** – formerly the nigrimaculella group; *** – Mediterranean P. matrona sp. nov., described below" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4554948" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4554948/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="344">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
); the signum is absent (
<taxonomicName box="[562,721,1303,1329]" class="Insecta" family="Opostegidae" genus="Pseudopostega" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="344" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="machaerias">
<emphasis box="[562,721,1303,1329]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="344">P. machaerias</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[736,837,1303,1329]" class="Insecta" family="Opostegidae" genus="Pseudopostega" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="344" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="zelopa">
<emphasis box="[736,837,1303,1329]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="344">P. zelopa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), weakly developed, indistinctive (
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Meyrick" baseAuthorityYear="1907" box="[1235,1364,1303,1328]" class="Insecta" family="Opostegidae" genus="Pseudopostega" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="344" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="epactaea">
<emphasis box="[1235,1364,1303,1328]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="344">P. epactaea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), well developed, lamellar (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Puplesis &amp; Robinson" authorityYear="1999" box="[388,553,1339,1365]" class="Insecta" family="Opostegidae" genus="Pseudopostega" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="344" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="parvilineata">
<emphasis box="[388,553,1339,1365]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="344">P. parvilineata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), or spiny (
<taxonomicName box="[683,853,1339,1365]" class="Insecta" family="Opostegidae" genus="Pseudopostega" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="344" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[683,853,1339,1365]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="344">Pseudopostega</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species 404).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="344" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1123,1617]" pageId="3" pageNumber="344">
From other groups of Oriental 
<taxonomicName box="[554,724,1375,1401]" class="Insecta" family="Opostegidae" genus="Pseudopostega" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="344" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[554,724,1375,1401]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="344">Pseudopostega</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the 
<taxonomicName box="[783,914,1375,1401]" class="Insecta" family="Opostegidae" genus="Pseudopostega" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="344" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="machaerias">
<emphasis box="[783,914,1375,1401]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="344">machaerias</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group is distinguished by the combination of dorsal markings of the forewing, and gnathos with a large plate and distinctive, wide, non-spiny caudal process.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="344" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1123,1617]" pageId="3" pageNumber="344">
Distribution. Currently the group is comprised of four named and one unnamed species (see Introduction) distributed in 
<collectingCountry box="[274,334,1483,1509]" name="India" pageId="3" pageNumber="344">India</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[346,416,1483,1509]" name="Nepal" pageId="3" pageNumber="344">Nepal</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[426,539,1483,1509]" name="Sri Lanka" pageId="3" pageNumber="344">Sri Lanka</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[550,662,1483,1509]" name="Indonesia" pageId="3" pageNumber="344">Indonesia</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[672,774,1483,1509]" name="Thailand" pageId="3" pageNumber="344">Thailand</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[786,915,1483,1509]" name="Philippines" pageId="3" pageNumber="344">Philippines</collectingCountry>
, and 
<collectingCountry box="[973,1059,1483,1509]" name="Taiwan" pageId="3" pageNumber="344">Taiwan</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="344" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1123,1617]" pageId="3" pageNumber="344">
Remarks. Previously, 
<taxonomicName box="[446,548,1519,1545]" class="Insecta" family="Opostegidae" genus="Pseudopostega" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="344" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="zelopa">
<emphasis box="[446,548,1519,1545]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="344">P. zelopa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was left unplaced in a species group (
<bibRefCitation author="Puplesis, R. &amp; Robinson, G. S." box="[981,1308,1519,1545]" pageId="3" pageNumber="344" pagination="1 - 92" refId="ref11121" refString="Puplesis, R. &amp; Robinson, G. S. (1999) Revision of the Oriental Opostegidae (Lepidoptera) with general comments on phylogeny within the family. Bulletin of the Natural History Museum, London, Entomology, 68 (1), 1 - 92." type="journal article" year="1999">Puplesis and Robinson 1999</bibRefCitation>
). However, upon on re-examination of males and females of 
<taxonomicName box="[699,800,1555,1581]" class="Insecta" family="Opostegidae" genus="Pseudopostega" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="344" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="zelopa">
<emphasis box="[699,800,1555,1581]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="344">P. zelopa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, we newly attribute this species to the 
<taxonomicName box="[1233,1364,1555,1581]" class="Insecta" family="Opostegidae" genus="Pseudopostega" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="344" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="machaerias">
<emphasis box="[1233,1364,1555,1581]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="344">machaerias</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group based on shared characters, including the apically widenned juxta in the male genitalia.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
